{"id":"1609.06126","submitter":"Jochen Szangolies","authors":"Jochen Szangolies, Hermann Kampermann, Dagmar Bru{\\ss}","title":"Device-Independent Bounds on Detection Efficiency","comments":"5 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 118, 260401 (2017)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.118.260401","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In many quantum information applications, a minimum detection efficiency must\nbe exceeded to ensure success. Protocols depending on the violation of a Bell\ninequality, for instance, may be subject to the so-called detection loophole:\nimperfect detectors may yield spurious violations, which consequently cannot be\nused to ensure, say, quantum cryptographic security. Hence, we investigate the\npossibility of giving lower bounds on detector efficiency even if an adversary\nhas full control over both the source and the detectors. To this end, we\npresent a technique to systematically derive Bell inequalities free from the\ndetection loophole using only the observed measurements statistics. The\nviolation of these inequalities certifies that the detectors used exceed a\ncertain minimal efficiency.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 20 Sep 2016 12:15:21 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 28 Jun 2017 16:27:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-06-29"}
